  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why are potassium supplements limited to 99mg?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The FDA limits over-the-counter potassium supplements to 99mg per serving as a safety measure to prevent hyperkalemia (dangerously high blood potassium). Rapid ingestion of concentrated potassium can disrupt heart rhythm and cause cardiac arrest in extreme cases. The 99mg limit applies to single-ingredient potassium supplements. This is just 2% of the 4,700mg Adequate Intake, which is why potassium should come primarily from food sources like bananas (422mg), potatoes (926mg), and spinach (839mg per cup).' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What are the symptoms of potassium deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Mild hypokalemia (low potassium) symptoms include muscle weakness, fatigue, cramps, and constipation. Moderate deficiency can cause irregular heartbeat (palpitations), increased blood pressure, and excessive urination. Severe hypokalemia (below 3.0 mEq/L) can cause paralysis, respiratory failure, and life-threatening cardiac arrhythmias. Common causes of potassium depletion include diuretic medications, excessive sweating, chronic diarrhea or vomiting, and diets low in fruits and vegetables.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How much potassium do I need per day?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The Adequate Intake (AI) for potassium is 2,600mg per day for adult women and 3,400mg per day for adult men, as established by the National Academies of Sciences in 2019. However, the average American consumes only about 2,500mg daily — a significant shortfall, especially for men. A potassium gummy providing 99mg supplements dietary intake but cannot come close to meeting the full daily requirement on its own. Focus on potassium-rich foods first and use gummies as supplemental support.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best form of potassium supplement?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Potassium citrate is generally considered the best supplemental form because it has higher bioavailability than potassium chloride and may help prevent kidney stones by alkalinizing urine. Potassium gluconate is well-tolerated and commonly used in gummies due to favorable taste characteristics. Potassium chloride is the most common prescription form and most closely mimics dietary potassium but has a strong salt-like taste that makes gummy formulation challenging. All three forms are effective for correcting mild deficiency.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take potassium with other supplements?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Potassium is generally safe to combine with most supplements. It pairs well with magnesium, as both minerals support muscle function, heart rhythm, and blood pressure regulation. However, potassium should be used cautiously with ACE inhibitors, ARBs (angiotensin receptor blockers), potassium-sparing diuretics, and certain heart medications that can raise potassium levels. If you take any blood pressure or heart medications, consult your physician before adding a potassium supplement.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is potassium good for high blood pressure?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Yes. A 2017 meta-analysis in the Journal of the American Heart Association found that increased potassium intake (from food and supplements) significantly reduced systolic blood pressure by an average of 4.48 mmHg. Potassium counteracts sodium-induced blood pressure elevation by promoting sodium excretion through the kidneys, relaxing blood vessel walls, and modulating the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. The DASH diet, which emphasizes potassium-rich foods, is a first-line recommendation for hypertension management.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Who should NOT take potassium supplements?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Individuals with kidney disease or impaired kidney function should not take potassium supplements without physician supervision, as the kidneys may not excrete excess potassium efficiently, leading to dangerous accumulation. Those taking potassium-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, triamterene), ACE inhibitors, or ARBs should avoid additional potassium supplementation. People with Addison\'s disease or other adrenal insufficiencies are also at risk for hyperkalemia. Always consult your healthcare provider if you have any kidney or cardiovascular condition.' },
