    <h2 id="why-potassium">Why Potassium Matters for Heart, Muscle, and Blood Pressure</h2>

    <p>Potassium is an essential electrolyte that enables every cell in your body to function. It maintains the electrical gradient across cell membranes — the voltage difference that allows nerves to fire, muscles to contract, and the heart to beat in a coordinated rhythm. Without adequate potassium, these fundamental biological processes break down: muscles cramp, fatigue sets in, blood pressure rises, and heart rhythm becomes irregular.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">98%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">of Americans do not meet the Adequate Intake for potassium (2,600mg for women, 3,400mg for men), according to the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES). <strong>This makes potassium the most under-consumed essential nutrient in the American diet.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <p>The FDA limits over-the-counter potassium supplements to 99mg per serving — just 2-4% of the daily Adequate Intake — as a safety precaution against hyperkalemia (dangerously high blood potassium). This means potassium gummies are a supplemental bridge, not a sole source. The primary potassium intake should come from food: potatoes, bananas, spinach, beans, and avocados. Gummies fill the gap for individuals whose diets fall short, particularly athletes who lose potassium through sweat, and older adults at risk for hypertension.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Potassium Gluconate</strong>
        <p>Well-tolerated form commonly used in gummies due to neutral taste. Contains 16.7% elemental potassium. Gentle on the stomach with minimal GI side effects. The most common form in consumer-grade potassium gummies.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Potassium Citrate</strong>
        <p>Higher bioavailability and may help prevent kidney stones by alkalinizing urine. Contains 38.3% elemental potassium. Preferred by urologists for patients at risk of calcium oxalate stones. Slightly tart taste that works well in gummy formulations.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Heart Rhythm & Blood Pressure</strong>
        <p>Potassium directly regulates the sodium-potassium pump in cardiac cells. Adequate intake reduces blood pressure by promoting sodium excretion and relaxing blood vessel walls. The DASH diet's blood pressure benefits are largely attributed to its high potassium content.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Muscle Function & Recovery</strong>
        <p>Potassium enables muscle contraction and relaxation by maintaining cell membrane potential. Deficiency causes cramps, weakness, and prolonged recovery. Athletes who sweat heavily lose significant potassium and benefit from supplementation during extended training.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <p>A 2017 meta-analysis published in the <em>Journal of the American Heart Association</em> examined 33 randomized controlled trials and found that increased potassium intake reduced <strong>systolic blood pressure by an average of 4.48 mmHg</strong> — a clinically meaningful reduction comparable to some first-line antihypertensive medications. The effect was strongest in individuals with high sodium diets.</p>
      <cite>Journal of the American Heart Association, 2017 — 33 RCTs, meta-analysis</cite>
    </div>

