    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Potassium Gummies</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why are potassium supplements limited to 99mg?</summary>
      <p>The FDA limits OTC potassium supplements to 99mg per serving to prevent hyperkalemia (dangerously high blood potassium). Rapid ingestion of concentrated potassium can disrupt heart rhythm. The 99mg limit is just 2-4% of the 4,700mg daily AI — potassium should come primarily from food sources like potatoes (926mg), spinach (839mg/cup), and bananas (422mg).</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What are the symptoms of potassium deficiency?</summary>
      <p>Mild: muscle weakness, fatigue, cramps, constipation. Moderate: irregular heartbeat, increased blood pressure, excessive urination. Severe (below 3.0 mEq/L): paralysis, respiratory failure, life-threatening cardiac arrhythmias. Common causes include diuretic medications, excessive sweating, chronic diarrhea, and diets low in fruits and vegetables.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much potassium do I need per day?</summary>
      <p>2,600mg for adult women, 3,400mg for adult men (Adequate Intake). The average American consumes about 2,500mg daily. A 99mg gummy supplements dietary intake but cannot meet the full requirement alone. Focus on potassium-rich foods first: potatoes, beans, spinach, avocados, bananas.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What is the best form of potassium supplement?</summary>
      <p>Potassium citrate has the highest bioavailability and may prevent kidney stones. Potassium gluconate is well-tolerated with minimal taste issues. Potassium chloride is most common in prescriptions but has a strong salt taste. All three effectively correct mild deficiency.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take potassium with other supplements?</summary>
      <p>Potassium pairs well with magnesium for muscle function and blood pressure. Use caution with ACE inhibitors, ARBs, potassium-sparing diuretics, and heart medications that can raise potassium levels. Consult your physician before supplementing if you take any blood pressure or cardiac medications.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is potassium good for high blood pressure?</summary>
      <p>Yes. A 2017 meta-analysis of 33 RCTs found increased potassium intake reduced systolic blood pressure by 4.48 mmHg on average. Potassium promotes sodium excretion and relaxes blood vessel walls. The DASH diet's blood pressure benefits are largely attributed to its high potassium content.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Who should NOT take potassium supplements?</summary>
      <p>Individuals with kidney disease, those taking potassium-sparing diuretics (spironolactone, triamterene), ACE inhibitors, ARBs, or those with Addison's disease. Impaired kidneys cannot excrete excess potassium efficiently, leading to dangerous accumulation. Always consult your healthcare provider if you have any kidney or cardiovascular condition.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What foods are highest in potassium?</summary>
      <p>White beans (1,004mg/cup), baked potato with skin (926mg), spinach cooked (839mg/cup), salmon (534mg/3oz), avocado (485mg/half), banana (422mg), coconut water (600mg/cup), orange juice (496mg/cup). Dietary potassium is always the preferred primary source over supplements.</p>
    </details>

